While building the AI-Assisted Margin and Shipping Exception Monitor, I learned that the project only becomes useful when the data contains real business exceptions to detect.

After joining the orders, costs, and shipments tables and adding the first business calculations, I confirmed three important signals:

Negative margins = orders where the total cost is higher than the selling price, meaning the business is losing money
Low margins = orders that are still profitable, but only slightly, making them financially risky
Positive delay days = shipments delivered after the promised date, meaning they are late

These are good signs for the MVP, because if none of these cases existed, the monitor would have nothing meaningful to flag.

What I learned
A working query is not enough; the joined dataset must also be validated for row count, duplicates, and nulls
LEFT JOIN was the right choice because orders are the main business grain and I wanted to keep all orders even if related data was missing
Business calculations such as margin value, margin percentage, and delay days are the foundation for later exception flags
The project is not just about SQL, but about translating raw data into business risk signals that teams can act on quickly
Business understanding gained

This project helped me think more clearly about how operational and financial issues can be turned into automated monitoring logic. Instead of manually checking rows, the goal is to automatically identify which orders need attention and make those risks visible through dashboards, workflows, and AI-generated summaries.
